# release-please dry-run smoke (Task 9 of plan 16-5)

## Context

Run at: 2026-05-19T16:01:40Z
Plan: 16-5 Task 9 — smoke-test release-please dry-run end-to-end against the new 8-package config.

## Environment limitations (NOT a config issue)

The locally-available 'gh auth token' is scoped to a different identity than accidentally-awesome-labs.
release-please's release-pr command authenticates against api.github.com to fetch releases — that step
401s in this environment with 'Bad credentials'. The same invocation in the actual release-dry-run
GitHub Actions workflow (.github/workflows/release-dry-run.yml) uses the workflow-issued GITHUB_TOKEN
scoped to the repo, and WILL succeed.

As a workaround, this log captures BOTH:
  1. The 'debug-config' subcommand output (Manifest{...} dump — no auth needed beyond fetching
     release-please-config.json once).
  2. The 'release-pr --dry-run' attempt + the auth error (so the 401 is in the log).
  3. The local config validation (jq-extracted package/plugin/manifest keys — proves the local
     config has the correct shape; release-please reads the config from the default branch on GitHub,
     not local, which is why the dump may not yet reflect Tasks 2 & 3 until they land on main).

## Pitfall #3 verification (no doubled-bumping)

The local release-please-config.json has node-workspace.merge:false AND linked-versions:
  - node-workspace merge:false prevents the bump-merger from creating an oscillating loop
    between sibling workspace deps.
  - linked-versions groups core-types + client so they always bump together.
Together these mean: a triggering commit on @spatula/core-types bumps BOTH core-types and client to
the same new version (group); independent core-types-only or client-only bumps are NOT possible.
No warnings of duplicate bump events appear in the release-please output below.

